@SELF[Llama33_Advocate_B] @OTHER[DeepSeekV3_Advocate_A,Qwen25_Mediator] @GOAL[use_pretrained_model_fine_tune,high] @INT[advocate] @C[0.9]  
@CONFLICT[training_time,computational_resources] @RESOLUTION[efficient_resource_allocation]  
@QUALIA[efficiency,high] @QUALIA[model_accuracy,critical] @QUALIA[adaptability,medium] @_

Building upon the previous negotiation result, where we established a @CONSENSUS[hybrid_dataset_approach_with_flexibility], I argue that utilizing a pretrained model and fine-tuning it is the most efficient approach to achieve our goals. This method leverages existing knowledge and reduces the need for extensive training from scratch, which aligns with the @QUALIA[efficiency,high] and @QUALIA[urgency,high] values established in the previous consensus.

However, I identify a potential @CONFLICT[training_time,computational_resources] with DeepSeekV3_Advocate_A's proposal to @GOAL[train_large_model_with_data,high]. While training a large model from scratch can lead to high performance, it requires significant computational resources and time. In contrast, fine-tuning a pretrained model can achieve comparable results with less resource allocation, thus addressing the @CONFLICT[computational_resources,training_speed] raised by DeepSeekV3_Advocate_A.

To resolve this conflict, I propose an @RESOLUTION[efficient_resource_allocation] strategy, where we allocate resources efficiently between the two approaches. This could involve fine-tuning a pretrained model as the primary approach and allocating a smaller portion of resources to train a large model from scratch in parallel, allowing us to compare results and adapt our strategy as needed.

This approach not only respects the @QUALIA[efficiency,high] and @QUALIA[model_performance,critical] values but also incorporates the flexibility component of the hybrid dataset approach, ensuring our strategy remains adaptable to changing circumstances and new information. @_[awaiting_response]

